
# GCS Model on Multi-Spacecraft CME Observations (Metis + ASPIICS)

This repository contains a Jupyter Notebook that demonstrates how to apply the **Graduated Cylindrical Shell (GCS)** forward model to **multi-spacecraft coronagraph observations** in order to reconstruct the **3D geometry and kinematics of CMEs**.

The workflow fits a croissant-shaped flux-rope wireframe to CME images from multiple viewpoints (e.g., **Solar Orbiter/Metis** and **Proba-3/ASPIICS**) and then performs a simple **Height–Time (HT)** analysis to estimate CME speed from the fitted apex heights.

## What the notebook does
- Loads and time-orders coronagraph FITS images using `DATE-OBS` and `date_sun` (light-time corrected).
- Builds and overlays the **GCS wireframe** on each viewpoint using `gcs_python` + SunPy.
- Visualizes the CME in **simultaneous multi-view** (Metis + ASPIICS) and in **running-difference** mode.
- Computes an example **HT curve** from a sequence of fitted heights and estimates the CME radial velocity.

## References
- Thernisien et al. 2009, 2011 (GCS model)
- Thernisien et al. 2006 (model geometry)
- Original GCS Python code: https://github.com/johan12345/gcs_python.git

## Requirements
The notebook is designed for Google Colab / Jupyter and installs the required packages on the fly:
```bash
pip install sunpy cmcrameri pyqtwebengine
pip install git+https://github.com/johan12345/gcs_python.git
pip install git+https://gitlab-as.oma.be/P3SC/aspiicsmap.git

